00:16:12,320 --> 00:16:17,840
know, over 1,000 or something. It was a big group. 
And it was the largest management job. I had  

185
00:16:17,840 --> 00:16:26,000
become a manager at Google, but a modest team. And 
so, I was doing okay but not great. And I had this  

186
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:32,720
moment where Sheryl saw me, I think I was editing 
a presentation for a partner just because the  

187
00:16:32,720 --> 00:16:37,920
presentation I got didn't meet my quality bar and 
I was editing it and griping about it. She pulled  

188
00:16:37,920 --> 00:16:44,800
me into a room and gave me talking to a little bit 
about holding my team to as high of a standard as  

189
00:16:44,800 --> 00:16:53,200
I have. If someone wasn't meeting my expectations, 
what was my plan to manage them out of the company  

190
00:16:53,200 --> 00:17:01,360
or... Just giving me management one-on-one.
And she's a remarkable mentor in the sense  

191
00:17:01,360 --> 00:17:06,400
she can give you feedback that's very 
direct and often, a bit uncomfortable,  

192
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:12,400
but you know she cares about you. And so it was 
the type of feedback you listen to. I went home  

193
00:17:12,400 --> 00:17:17,280
that night and I was stewing on it and not very 
happy. I was like, you get naturally a little  

194
00:17:17,280 --> 00:17:23,040
defensive in those moments. Is that really true? 
Am I really fucking it up or is she overreacting?  

195
00:17:23,040 --> 00:17:30,320
And then I woke up the next day, I was like, "No, 
she's right." And I had realized this subconscious  

196
00:17:30,320 --> 00:17:38,000
limiter that was limiting my success in the job, 
which is, I was trying to conform the job to the  

197
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:43,840
things I thought I liked to do. So, I was spending 
a lot of my time on some product and technology  

198
00:17:43,840 --> 00:17:50,400
things that I was passionate about, thinking I'm 
the boss. I should focus on what I want to focus  

199
00:17:50,400 --> 00:17:56,560
on instead of thinking about, okay, I'm running 
the mobile and platform teams at Facebook. What's  

200
00:17:56,560 --> 00:18:03,040
the most important thing to do today to make 
our mobile and developer platform successful? 

201
00:18:03,040 --> 00:18:09,920
And when I reframed the job that way, I did 
different things. And the thing that was the  

202
00:18:09,920 --> 00:18:16,080
biggest pleasant surprise to me was I liked 
it. I thought I liked engineering and product,  

203
00:18:16,080 --> 00:18:21,120
but in fact, when I changed an organization 
and it turned out to be more successful,  

204
00:18:21,120 --> 00:18:27,120
I derived a great deal of joy from seeing that 
success. Our developer platform had a lot of  

205
00:18:27,120 --> 00:18:31,120
partners and when there was an issue there and 
I'd spend time on partnerships and it worked  

206
00:18:31,120 --> 00:18:36,480
and our platform became healthier, the partner 
became more successful. I took pride in that  

207
00:18:36,480 --> 00:18:44,320
success and then I just started being better 
at my job and I realized that the actual act  

208
00:18:44,320 --> 00:18:48,960
of engineering or product design or all the things 
I thought I liked, what I really liked is impact. 

209
00:18:48,960 --> 00:18:57,600
And so, that conversation led to my waking up 
every morning, sometimes literally, but certainly,  

210
00:18:57,600 --> 00:19:02,480
in the broadest sets of the words saying, "What 
is the most impactful thing I can do today?" And  

211
00:19:02,480 --> 00:19:09,600
really thinking almost like, if you had an 
external board of advisors telling you what  

212
00:19:09,600 --> 00:19:14,320
are the things where if you focus on them, you 
can maximize the likelihood that what you're  

213
00:19:14,320 --> 00:19:20,000
trying to achieve will happen? Sometimes, it's 
recruiting, sometimes, it's product, sometimes,  

214
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:25,120
it's engineering, sometimes, it's sales. And I've 
become much more self-reflective just about what  

215
00:19:25,120 --> 00:19:32,240
is important to work on. And I have become much 
more receptive to doing things that I previously  

216
00:19:32,240 --> 00:19:36,400
would've said aren't my favorite things to do 
because I derive so much joy from having an  

217
00:19:36,400 --> 00:19:41,760
impact that I enjoy a lot more things now. And 
so, I really credit Sheryl, I'm so grateful.  

218
00:19:41,760 --> 00:19:45,520
And actually, it's interesting, I think a lot 
about this when I give feedback to people now,  

219
00:19:45,520 --> 00:19:53,680
just those moments that can change the trajectory 
of your career. I give her all the credit for it.

220
00:19:53,680 --> 00:19:56,320
There's so many people that share 
stories of Sheryl Sandberg giving  

221
00:19:56,320 --> 00:20:01,200
them advice and that changing 
their life. What a mensch.

222
00:20:01,200 --> 00:20:01,520
Yeah.

223
00:20:01,520 --> 00:20:04,880
My biggest takeaway from this, which 
is this question of what is the most  

224
00:20:04,880 --> 00:20:09,520
impactful thing I could do today? Such a powerful 
heuristic just to keep in mind. To your point,  

225
00:20:09,520 --> 00:20:14,320
you may realize you don't want to be doing sales 
or hiring, but if that's the most impactful thing  

226
00:20:14,320 --> 00:20:18,160
and you end up doing it, you may realize I like 
this and I'm good at this and have thought about-

227
00:20:18,160 --> 00:20:19,760
Can I double click on that though for a second?

228
00:20:19,760 --> 00:20:20,240
Absolutely.

229
00:20:20,240 --> 00:20:26,160
I think it's really hard. One of the 
dangers for founders and product managers,  

230
00:20:26,160 --> 00:20:32,960
but I think particularly for founders 
is incorrect storytelling. People don't  

231
00:20:32,960 --> 00:20:38,000
like my product because of X. And if you tell 
that to yourself and you tell it to your team,  

232
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:43,040
all of a sudden, it goes from being an intuition 
to being a fact. Well, you better hope you're  

233
00:20:43,040 --> 00:20:50,240
right because if you orient your strategy 
around fixing a problem and you're wrong,  

234
00:20:50,240 --> 00:20:58,080
your company's going to fail. So why did you lose 
a deal? You could talk to the salesperson who is  

235
00:20:58,080 --> 00:21:03,200
on the account or perhaps maybe a product 
manager was involved in the conversation.  

236
00:21:03,200 --> 00:21:07,600
It's very important to have intellectual 
honesty in those moments because you could  

237
00:21:07,600 --> 00:21:13,040
say something like, "Oh, they didn't buy 
it because the platform cost too much."  

238
00:21:13,680 --> 00:21:18,960
And that's something a salesperson might say.
Maybe the real reason is they didn't actually  

239
00:21:18,960 --> 00:21:24,240
see much value in your platform. So it was 
communicated to the salesperson as it was  

240
00:21:24,240 --> 00:21:29,120
too expensive. But in fact, the problem was 
product differentiation. And you could end up  

241
00:21:29,120 --> 00:21:35,360
going into a discussion on pricing when in fact, 
there was a much deeper, much harder problem to  

242
00:21:35,360 --> 00:21:40,800
solve there. But just like when you break up 
with someone, you don't say, it's because I  

243
00:21:40,800 --> 00:21:45,040
don't like you anymore. You say it's not you, 
it's me. You say all these pleasantries because  

244
00:21:45,040 --> 00:21:51,760
we're all social animals and you want to 
be pleasant with the people around you.  

245
00:21:51,760 --> 00:21:58,080
So literally taking what a customer says or what a 
user says in a focus group or a usability study is  

246
00:21:58,080 --> 00:22:06,160
rarely correct. It often is related to what the 
truth is, but it's very important to get right.  

247
00:22:06,160 --> 00:22:11,440
And so, I think one of the things I've observed 
with first time founders in particular is you're  

248
00:22:11,440 --> 00:22:17,200
often a single issue voter based on your skillset.
So if you're a great engineer, the answer to  

249
00:22:17,200 --> 00:22:20,640
almost every problem in your business is 
engineering. If you're a product designer,  

250
00:22:20,640 --> 00:22:25,920
the answer almost to the proverbial redesign, 
I joke, it's like the dead cap balance of a  

251
00:22:25,920 --> 00:22:30,640
consumer product like this next redesign will fix 
all of our problems. I don't know if it's ever,  

252
00:22:30,640 --> 00:22:36,720
ever worked. And then I met a lot of entrepreneurs 
who come from a business development background,  

253
00:22:36,720 --> 00:22:41,440
they're always thinking about partnerships and 
oh, if we just get this partnership done for  

254
00:22:41,440 --> 00:22:46,960
this distribution channel, everything's going to 
change. And I think it's really important when  

255
00:22:46,960 --> 00:22:54,240
you're a founder to be self-aware that you will 
naturally, subconsciously pick the thing that is  

256
00:22:54,240 --> 00:22:59,840
your strength, your superpower as a solution to 
more problems. And in fact, if you think that's  

257
00:22:59,840 --> 00:23:03,920
a solution to your problem, it may be right, 
but you probably by default should question it. 

258
00:23:03,920 --> 00:23:09,280
If you think the thing that you've been doing 
your whole career is the way to fix your problem,  

259
00:23:09,280 --> 00:23:15,600
it's at least 30% likely that you've chosen 
that because of comfort and familiarity not  

260
00:23:15,600 --> 00:23:21,760
truth. And so, I think one of the skills I think 
is, it really goes around to do you have a good  

261
00:23:21,760 --> 00:23:27,040
co-founder? Do you have a good leadership team? 
If you're a product manager, you're a partner  

262
00:23:27,040 --> 00:23:32,240
in engineering, you're a partner in marketing, 
you really want to have very real conversations  

263
00:23:32,240 --> 00:23:36,800
to ensure that you're actually working on the 
actual correct thing. And I think it's easy  

264
00:23:36,800 --> 00:23:41,760
to say what's the most impactful thing to do 
today? My guess, if a lot of people try that,  

265
00:23:41,760 --> 00:23:45,360
they'll lie to themselves more often than 
not. And it's a very challenging question  

266
00:23:45,360 --> 00:23:50,400
to answer. The question's interesting. Being able 
to answer it accurately is actually the hard part.

267
00:23:50,400 --> 00:23:54,640
This feels like such an important lesson 
you've learned. Is there an example that  

268
00:23:54,640 --> 00:23:58,790
comes to mind where you learned this the 
hard way where you actually ended up-

269
00:23:58,790 --> 00:24:01,520
Oh, yeah. You just want to spend this whole 
thing on my failures, but I'm fine with that.

270
00:24:02,720 --> 00:24:04,080
You've had too much success.

271
00:24:04,080 --> 00:24:10,320
Frontier was my first company. At our peak we 
had 12 employees, 12 of the best people I've ever  

272
00:24:10,320 --> 00:24:15,360
worked with. Started the company with Jim Norris, 
who's an engineer I've known since Stanford and  

273
00:24:15,360 --> 00:24:20,560
Paul Buhite and Sanjeev Singh who Paul started 
Gmail. Sanjeev was the first engineer at Gmail,  

274
00:24:20,560 --> 00:24:25,520
so we had the Google Maps people and 
Gmail people. It was a pretty awesome  

275
00:24:25,520 --> 00:24:33,360
founding team. We made a social network, as you 
said. We invented a lot of concepts that became  

276
00:24:33,360 --> 00:24:38,880
popular in the newsfeed. We invented the like 
button. It was really neat. It was a fun time.  

277
00:24:38,880 --> 00:24:43,200
We were only really popular in Turkey, Italy and 
Iran, and at one point, we were blocked in Iran,  

278
00:24:43,200 --> 00:24:47,280
so we were only popular in Turkey and Italy 
and Silicon Valley. To this day, actually a  

279
00:24:47,280 --> 00:24:51,280
lot of folks in Silicon Valley are like, "I 
love FriendFeed." I'm like, that's awesome. 

280
00:24:51,280 --> 00:24:58,480
It wasn't really a successful business. We 
were a follower-oriented social network,  

281
00:24:58,480 --> 00:25:02,000
not a friendship-oriented social network, 
which meant a lot of our content was more  

282
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:08,000
like X or Twitter than it is Facebook in that 
respect. And a lot of sharing newspaper articles,  

283
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:16,000
interests, scientific communities, things like 
that. And there was a period when Twitter,  

284
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:19,200
which was one of our competitors at the 
time, that there was a lot more social  

285
00:25:19,200 --> 00:25:24,400
networks at the time. I am probably screwing 
this up a little bit. I think Obama, Ashton  

286
00:25:24,400 --> 00:25:30,240
Kutcher and Oprah Winfrey all went on Twitter 
in a summer and we just got our ass kicked. 

287
00:25:31,200 --> 00:25:37,440
And it was a great example of you... I think 
11 of those 12 people were engineers and we  

288
00:25:37,440 --> 00:25:42,400
were just making product and I think it was 
Biz Stone. If you talk to the Twitter folks,  

289
00:25:42,400 --> 00:25:46,560
they could give you the history on this, but 
I think Biz was really focused on getting  

290
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:52,800
celebrities and public figures onto Twitter, which 
is totally obvious. If you have a social service  

291
00:25:52,800 --> 00:25:57,760
that's oriented towards following people, put some 
people on there worth following and instead, we  

292
00:25:57,760 --> 00:26:05,760
were exclusively focused on polishing the product.
And we actually, I think at our peak of  

293
00:26:05,760 --> 00:26:10,160
popularity, we were very confident just, I think 
it was a time when Twitter had the fail whale  

294
00:26:10,160 --> 00:26:15,520
and it was down half the time and people couldn't 
even use it. And our product, we were innovating  

295
00:26:15,520 --> 00:26:22,480
faster, we had more features, people liked it and 
we were up 100% of the time and we totally lost  

296
00:26:22,480 --> 00:26:29,520
for no reason related to product at all. And it 
was an example of, I think somewhat famously not  

297
00:26:29,520 --> 00:26:33,760
a lot of great entrepreneurs have come out 
of Google because Google was so successful,  

298
00:26:33,760 --> 00:26:40,240
I think it's hard as a product manager to see 
distribution and product design and even business  

299
00:26:40,240 --> 00:26:46,960
model when you have AdWords and money's raining 
from the sky. There wasn't as much scrutiny and I  

300
00:26:46,960 --> 00:26:52,480
think folks like the PayPal Mafia I think learned 
a lot more about entrepreneurialism than a typical  

301
00:26:52,480 --> 00:26:57,120
PM at Google. So, we're just getting punched 
in the face and learning this the hard way. 

302
00:26:57,120 --> 00:27:01,040
And so, that was probably the most prominent 
example of it and I think we probably did have  

303
00:27:01,040 --> 00:27:04,720
a... I can tell you all the flaws of that 
product, but I don't think that was the  

304
00:27:04,720 --> 00:27:08,960
reason why we lost. There's a lot of reasons. I 
think there was a lot of flaws of the product,  

305
00:27:08,960 --> 00:27:14,640
but it was a lot of other stuff. And so, I've 
learned, accumulated these skills over time,  

306
00:27:14,640 --> 00:27:18,880
but I say the hard part of that question is 
answering it correctly, is it's hard when you  

307
00:27:18,880 --> 00:27:22,800
don't have experience in something, than to have 
intuition in it. So I think if there's probably a  

308
00:27:22,800 --> 00:27:27,360
structural flaw, it wasn't that... I don't know 
if I could have figured out how to reach out to  

309
00:27:27,360 --> 00:27:33,840
Ashton Kutcher [inaudible 00:27:28], it's 
not he's on my Rolodex. But I probably  

310
00:27:33,840 --> 00:27:38,320
wasn't soliciting advice from the right people.
I think that what's great about the technology  

311
00:27:38,320 --> 00:27:44,080
industry is there's a lot of advice. Choosing whom 
you listen to is actually quite difficult, but  

312
00:27:44,080 --> 00:27:49,760
I think we're somewhat myopic. We're in our own 
little world, creating this product and we weren't  

313
00:27:49,760 --> 00:27:55,600
asking people from the outside in to say, what 
are you seeing that could go wrong? What are you  

314
00:27:55,600 --> 00:27:59,840
seeing that could go right? What are you seeing in 
the industry that we're not doing that you think  

315
00:27:59,840 --> 00:28:05,520
we might want to do? And this is why boards are 
important. This is why finding the right advisors,  

316
00:28:05,520 --> 00:28:10,000
the advisors will actually tell you what you not 
[inaudible 00:28:09] want to hear, but you need to  

317
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:14,800
hear. I think that was probably the missing part. 
I'm not sure I was great at market at the time,  

318
00:28:14,800 --> 00:28:20,960
but if I had solicited the right advice, I could 
have learned that that was a shortcoming. And I  

319
00:28:20,960 --> 00:28:26,320
think that was a deep lesson I took from that. I'm 
a huge believer in boards and getting good advice.

320
00:28:26,320 --> 00:28:31,280
Any heuristics or advice for people to 
know whose advice to listen to? What do  

321
00:28:31,280 --> 00:28:35,120
you pay attention to when you're like, okay, 
ignore this person but listen to this person?

322
00:28:35,120 --> 00:28:42,800
Yeah, that one's tough. It does come down to good 
judgment and being judge of people's character.  

323
00:28:42,800 --> 00:28:48,720
One thing that is particularly hard is there's 
not a strong correlation between the confidence  

324
00:28:48,720 --> 00:28:53,120
with which someone expresses an opinion 
and the quality of that opinion. I don't  

325
00:28:53,120 --> 00:28:59,040
want to say it's inversely correlated, but 
that's funny, with all the podcasts out now,  

326
00:28:59,040 --> 00:29:04,960
if there's topics I know a lot about, sometimes 
the most eloquent, confident statements about  

327
00:29:04,960 --> 00:29:11,680
things I know a lot about, are the least accurate 
and it sounds extremely persuasive. And so,  

328
00:29:11,680 --> 00:29:17,760
it does require very good judgment. One thing is 
I think, not just asking for advice but asking  

329
00:29:17,760 --> 00:29:22,240
people, who should I talk to get good advice? And 
you'll find some common answers there and that's  

330
00:29:22,240 --> 00:29:30,000
often a really strong signal of good judgment.
And then one thing I found is when you ask for  

331
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:35,360
advice, don't just ask what to do but why. Be 
an obnoxious two-year-old kid, why? Why? Why?  

332
00:29:35,360 --> 00:29:41,920
Why? And really try to understand the framework 
that someone is using to give you advice. The  

333
00:29:41,920 --> 00:29:47,600
interesting thing about advice is people are often 
extrapolating from relatively few experiences.  

334
00:29:47,600 --> 00:29:53,760
So they will say, never do this or always do 
that. And it's because they had one experience  

335
00:29:53,760 --> 00:29:59,360
where something backfired or something could have 
gone better if they had done it. So it's a useful  

336
00:29:59,360 --> 00:30:04,000
anecdote, but if you don't ask why and understand 
they had one experience and here's what happened,  

337
00:30:04,560 --> 00:30:09,520
it can come across as a rule when in fact, 
it's [inaudible 00:30:08] data and if you  

338
00:30:09,520 --> 00:30:14,080
ask advice of three people and they all have 
very similar interactions, you can create  

339
00:30:14,080 --> 00:30:19,520
a first principles framework from which that 
advice emerges. And when you start applying it,  

340
00:30:19,520 --> 00:30:24,560
you're applying it with a degree of nuance that 
you couldn't if you're just following a rule. So,  

341
00:30:24,560 --> 00:30:30,720
I think one is, it does come down to good 
judgment, I think. I don't know how to teach that. 

342
00:30:33,360 --> 00:30:36,480
I'm a huge believer in good judgment. It's 
one of the things I hire for. I just think  

343
00:30:36,480 --> 00:30:43,040
that's something that probably comes from a 
mix of self perfection. You really need to  

344
00:30:43,040 --> 00:30:48,160
hold yourselves accountable as an entrepreneur, 
as a product manager. If you made a bad decision,  

345
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:53,760
spend time reflecting on it, number one. And 
really, try to understand why and try to always  

346
00:30:53,760 --> 00:30:58,480
improve your judgment. I think at the end of the 
day, that is why you are a good entrepreneur,  

347
00:30:58,480 --> 00:31:03,040
a good product manager. And number two, when 
you get advice, really understand where it's  

348
00:31:03,040 --> 00:31:09,760
coming from and why so that you can create your 
own independent view of where that advice came  

349
00:31:09,760 --> 00:31:14,720
from and recognize that no one's advice is 
statistically significant or very rarely is  

350
00:31:14,720 --> 00:31:19,280
it. If you're getting advice on investing from 
Warren Buffett, yeah, okay, it's statistically  

351
00:31:19,280 --> 00:31:24,800
significant, but most advice is like something 
happened to you once and you have regrets.

352
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:29,040
I love that you're like, I don't know if I 
have a great answer then you just give us  

353
00:31:29,040 --> 00:31:32,800
an incredible answer to this question. I want to 
go in a different direction. You mentioned that  

354
00:31:32,800 --> 00:31:38,080
you describe yourself as an engineer. I know I 
heard you code to relax still. Let me just ask  

355
00:31:38,080 --> 00:31:41,600
you this question, something a lot of people in 
college are thinking about. Do you think it still  

356
00:31:41,600 --> 00:31:46,480
makes sense to learn to code? Do you think this 
will significantly change in the next few years?

357
00:31:46,480 --> 00:31:52,320
I do still think studying computer science 
is a different answer than learning to code,  

358
00:31:52,320 --> 00:31:58,240
but I would say I still think it's extremely 
valuable to study computer science. I say that  

359
00:31:58,240 --> 00:32:03,120
because I think computer science is more than 
coding. If you understand things like Big O  

360
00:32:03,120 --> 00:32:17,600
notation or complexity theory or study algorithms 
and why a randomized algorithm works and why two  

361
00:32:17,600 --> 00:32:23,200
algorithms with the same Big O complexity, one can 
then practice perform better than others and why a  

362
00:32:23,200 --> 00:32:28,160
cache miss matters and just all these little... 
There's a lot more to coding than writing the  

363
00:32:28,160 --> 00:32:35,920
code. The reason I think that is I do think the 
act of creating software is going to transform  

364
00:32:35,920 --> 00:32:44,000
from typing into a terminal or typing into 
Visual Studio code to operating a code-generating  

