01:06:00,480 --> 01:06:06,880
phone," there's a pre-negotiated rate for that 
and we call it resolution based. There are other  

730
01:06:06,880 --> 01:06:12,400
outcomes as well. We have some sales agents being 
paid a sales commission, believe it or not. We do.  

731
01:06:12,400 --> 01:06:16,960
We really think of our agents as truly customer 
experience like the concierge for your brand and  

732
01:06:16,960 --> 01:06:22,640
we want to make sure that our business model 
is aligned with our customer's business model. 

733
01:06:22,640 --> 01:06:25,520
As you said, these agents need to be 
autonomous and the outcome has to be  

734
01:06:25,520 --> 01:06:30,000
measurable. That's not always possible, but I 
think it's broadly possible. And what's really  

735
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:36,960
neat about it is if you talk to any CFO or 
head of procurement with their big vendors,  

736
01:06:36,960 --> 01:06:42,160
they look at the bill of materials and it's 
overwhelming and it's impossible to know if  

737
01:06:42,160 --> 01:06:48,640
you're getting the value that you hoped from that 
contract. I think consumption based, which was  

738
01:06:48,640 --> 01:06:53,200
popular particularly in the infrastructure 
space is closer to it. But I'm not sure a  

739
01:06:53,200 --> 01:06:59,760
token is actually a good measure of value from AI 
either. I always use the analogy, like right now,  

740
01:06:59,760 --> 01:07:05,600
most of the coding agents are priced per token or 
per utilization, but there's this famous story of  

741
01:07:05,600 --> 01:07:10,560
an Apple engineer who had a bad manager who's 
like had you report how many lines of code you  

742
01:07:10,560 --> 01:07:15,920
wrote every day? Which every engineer in the world 
knows is an idiotic way to measure productivity. 

743
01:07:15,920 --> 01:07:19,280
He famously went in with a report that had a 
negative number because I think he did a big  

744
01:07:19,280 --> 01:07:23,760
refactoring, deleted a bunch and it was his 
way of saying like, fuck you to the man. I  

745
01:07:23,760 --> 01:07:30,320
think tokens are similar. Yeah, you used a lot 
of tokens, like good for you, did it produce a  

746
01:07:30,320 --> 01:07:36,160
pull request that was good? And I think that's 
the whole point of all this. I think there's  

747
01:07:36,160 --> 01:07:42,400
a huge difference between outcomes-based pricing 
and usage based pricing because especially in AI,  

748
01:07:42,400 --> 01:07:46,480
they're not necessarily even correlated and you 
could have a long phone call and not solve the  

749
01:07:46,480 --> 01:07:51,920
customer's problem and they give you a negative 
review online and call the call center again,  

750
01:07:51,920 --> 01:07:56,480
all that effort was for nothing. In fact, 
you might've added negative value. And so,  

751
01:07:56,480 --> 01:08:00,000
I am a huge believer in this.
And what's fun about it is it  

752
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:05,280
really just aligns... I think every technology 
company aspires to be a partner, not a vendor.  

753
01:08:05,280 --> 01:08:09,840
And I think at Sierra, we are truly a partner 
to every single one of our customers because  

754
01:08:09,840 --> 01:08:15,520
we're all aligned on what we want to achieve. And 
I think that is really where the software industry  

755
01:08:15,520 --> 01:08:22,320
should go. It requires a lot of different shape 
of a company. You have to be able to help your  

756
01:08:22,320 --> 01:08:26,000
customers achieve those outcomes. You can't just 
throw software at the wall because you'll never  

757
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:34,560
get paid if it doesn't. Your orientation becomes 
so extremely customer-centric when you do this the  

758
01:08:34,560 --> 01:08:39,360
right way. I think it's just a better version of 
the software industry. So I think it's right from  

759
01:08:39,360 --> 01:08:43,200
first principles, it's right for procurement 
partners and I think it's right for the world.

760
01:08:43,200 --> 01:08:46,400
We've been chatting a little 
bit about productivity gains.  

761
01:08:46,400 --> 01:08:50,880
There's a lot of skepticism in the headlines 
these days of just like what is AI actually  

762
01:08:50,880 --> 01:08:54,560
doing? Is it actually helping people be more 
productive? There was a recent study actually,  

763
01:08:54,560 --> 01:08:57,840
I don't know if you saw, where they 
showed engineers were less productive  

764
01:08:57,840 --> 01:09:00,960
with AI because it was just putting them in 
different directions. They had to research  

765
01:09:00,960 --> 01:09:05,120
all what's going wrong here? So I think CX is 
a really good example where you clearly are  

766
01:09:05,120 --> 01:09:10,240
seeing gains. Are you seeing actual gains at your 
company or any other company you work with outside  

767
01:09:10,240 --> 01:09:15,280
of CX in terms of productivity that is like 
clearly yes, this is working and a huge deal?

768
01:09:15,280 --> 01:09:21,760
I'm extremely bullish on the productivity gains 
from AI, but I do think the tools and products  

769
01:09:21,760 --> 01:09:28,720
right now are somewhat immature and it's quite 
counterintuitive. So, for example, almost every  

770
01:09:28,720 --> 01:09:34,160
