like Cursor to help their software engineers.  

771
01:09:34,160 --> 01:09:40,160
Most people use Cursor right now as a coding 
autocomplete, though they have a lot of agentic  

772
01:09:40,160 --> 01:09:46,480
solutions and there's a lot of... OpenAI has Codex 
and Cloud has... I can't remember the Anthropic  

773
01:09:46,480 --> 01:09:51,520
products. So there's lots of agentic agents 
coming as well. One of the interesting things  

774
01:09:51,520 --> 01:09:58,320
because the technology is immature, the code it 
produces often has problems. There's a lot of  

775
01:09:58,320 --> 01:10:04,000
people approaching this to actually realize those 
productivity gains because as any engineer who's  

776
01:10:04,000 --> 01:10:10,560
written a lot of code will tell you, it's pretty 
easy to look at and edit and fix code you wrote. 

777
01:10:10,560 --> 01:10:15,920
Reviewing other people's code or particularly 
finding a subtle logical error in someone else's  

778
01:10:15,920 --> 01:10:22,240
code is actually really hard. It's actually much 
harder than editing code that you wrote yourself.  

779
01:10:22,240 --> 01:10:29,120
So if the code produced by a coding agent is often 
incorrect, it actually can take a lot of cognitive  

780
01:10:29,120 --> 01:10:36,320
load and time to fix it. And in fact, if you end 
up producing lots of issues with your customers,  

781
01:10:36,320 --> 01:10:41,600
you could end up producing a lot of features, 
but actually, is like mucking up the machine  

782
01:10:41,600 --> 01:10:45,600
a little bit and having something that's not 
ideal. There's a couple of techniques that I  

783
01:10:45,600 --> 01:10:49,760
think are interesting. First, I think there's a 
lot of AI starts now working on things like code  

784
01:10:49,760 --> 01:10:55,280
reviews. I think this idea of self-reflection in 
agents is really important. Having AI supervise  

785
01:10:55,280 --> 01:11:00,160
the AI is actually very effective. Just think 
about it this way, if you produce an AI agent  

786
01:11:00,160 --> 01:11:05,120
that's right 90% of the time, that's not that 
great, but how hard would it be to make another  

787
01:11:05,120 --> 01:11:10,160
AI agent to find the errors the other 10% of 
the time? That might be a tractable problem. 

788
01:11:10,160 --> 01:11:14,480
And if that thing's right 90% of the time, just 
for argument's sake, you can wire those things  

789
01:11:14,480 --> 01:11:19,760
together and have something that's right 99% 
of the time. So it's just a math problem and  

790
01:11:19,760 --> 01:11:23,280
it turns out that you can make something 
to generate code, you can make something  

791
01:11:23,280 --> 01:11:28,080
to review code and you're essentially using 
compute for cognitive capacity and you can  

792
01:11:28,080 --> 01:11:34,320
layer on more layers of cognition and thinking 
and reasoning and produce things increasingly  

793
01:11:34,320 --> 01:11:40,240
robust. So I'm very excited about that. The other 
thing though is root cause analysis. So we have an  

794
01:11:40,240 --> 01:11:48,080
engineer at Sierra who exclusively focuses on the 
model context protocol server serving our cursor  

795
01:11:48,080 --> 01:11:54,720
instance. And our whole philosophy is, if cursor 
generated something incorrect, rather than just  

796
01:11:54,720 --> 01:12:01,600
fixing it, try to root cause it. Try to get it so 
the next time Cursor will produce the correct code  

797
01:12:02,720 --> 01:12:08,640
and essentially, is context engineering.
What context did Cursor not have that would've  

798
01:12:08,640 --> 01:12:13,280
been necessary to produce the right outcome? So 
I think people who are trying to get productivity  

799
01:12:13,280 --> 01:12:18,800
gains in departments like software engineering 
need to stop waiting for the models to magically  

800
01:12:18,800 --> 01:12:23,360
work if they want to see the gains now. And you 
really have to create root cause analysis and  

801
01:12:23,360 --> 01:12:30,640
systems and say, how do we go root cause every bad 
line of code and actually give the right context  

802
01:12:30,640 --> 01:12:35,600
and produce the right system so the models can 
do it today? Over time that'll probably be less  

803
01:12:35,600 --> 01:12:40,640
necessary and you'll have less context engineering 
necessary to do it, but you really have to think  

804
01:12:40,640 --> 01:12:45,840
of this as a system and I think people are waiting 
for the models to just magically get better. And  

805
01:12:45,840 --> 01:12:50,800
I'm like, well that will happen eventually, but if 
you want the gains now you got to put in the work.  

806
01:12:50,800 --> 01:12:56,320
That's essentially why applied AI companies exist.
And the work is non-trivial, but you can do it.  

807
01:12:56,320 --> 01:13:01,600
And so, for customers using platforms like Sierra, 
yeah, AI agents aren't perfect, but we're creating  

808
01:13:01,600 --> 01:13:05,760
a system that lets customers create a virtuous 
cycle of improvement. If you want to go from a  

809
01:13:05,760 --> 01:13:12,640
65% automated resolution rate to 75%, we have 
a billion tools to let AI help you do that,  

810
01:13:12,640 --> 01:13:17,280
identify opportunities for improvement, figure out 
why people are frustrated, what new capabilities  

811
01:13:17,280 --> 01:13:23,920
can we add to our agent to improve the resolution 
rate? And you let AI put the needles at the  

812
01:13:23,920 --> 01:13:28,080
top of the haystack on your behalf and I think 
that's really the way to optimize these systems.

813
01:13:28,080 --> 01:13:32,320
I've never heard of this technique of 
improving Cursor by adding additional  

814
01:13:32,320 --> 01:13:37,440
context. What's the actual way of doing that? 
You build an MCP server that everything runs  

815
01:13:37,440 --> 01:13:40,960
through or is it like you add Cursor 
rules? What's the actual approach there?

816
01:13:40,960 --> 01:13:46,640
I'm probably out of my depth here, but it's 
essentially MCP because that's how you provide  

817
01:13:46,640 --> 01:13:51,680
context to Cursor. And I think that almost always 
when you have a model making a poor decision,  

818
01:13:51,680 --> 01:13:57,200
if it's a good model, it's lack of context. And 
so, you really want to find the intersection of  

819
01:13:57,200 --> 01:14:02,640
your particular product and code base with 
the context available to these coding agents  

820
01:14:02,640 --> 01:14:06,640
and systems and fix it at the 
root is the principle here.

821
01:14:06,640 --> 01:14:10,240
Got it. That is very cool. I hadn't heard of 
people doing that, model context protocol,  

822
01:14:10,240 --> 01:14:14,000
makes sense. We've talked about productivity gains 
outside TX. Just to give you a chance to share  

823
01:14:14,000 --> 01:14:18,880
how amazing what you've built is, what are some 
