859
01:17:35,360 --> 01:17:41,600
I think there's a small handful of go-to-market 
models that have been proven to work, and I think  

860
01:17:41,600 --> 01:17:47,600
it's important to choose the right one for the 
product category you're going after. One category  

861
01:17:47,600 --> 01:17:54,080
I would say is developer-led. This is somewhere 
famously Stripe and Twilio where probably two  

862
01:17:54,080 --> 01:17:59,440
of the original that did this exceptionally. And 
essentially, the go-to-market motion there is to  

863
01:17:59,440 --> 01:18:06,960
appeal to an individual engineer often within the 
department of the CTO who have accountability and  

864
01:18:06,960 --> 01:18:16,960
a fair amount of latitude to choose a solution. 
This works if your product is a platform product.  

865
01:18:16,960 --> 01:18:22,000
It doesn't work, for example, if your product 
is trying to help a line of business because  

866
01:18:22,000 --> 01:18:27,920
lines of business typically don't have dedicated 
engineering teams or let alone, the latitude to  

867
01:18:27,920 --> 01:18:34,160
just go download a new library or start using a 
web service like that. It particularly works well  

868
01:18:34,160 --> 01:18:37,840
if you sell to startups just because startups 
tend to have engineering teams with quite a  

869
01:18:37,840 --> 01:18:43,920
bit of latitude to choose services to help 
them solve the problem given by the founder. 

870
01:18:43,920 --> 01:18:49,360
Then there's product-led growth. It's a broad 
term, obviously every company's product matters,  

871
01:18:49,360 --> 01:18:54,640
but product-led growth more specifically 
means users can sign up from the website,  

872
01:18:54,640 --> 01:18:59,280
often get put on a trial. Often you can buy a 
couple of seats with a credit card and those  

873
01:18:59,280 --> 01:19:04,080
work where your user and your buyer are the 
same person. So it works for small business  

874
01:19:04,080 --> 01:19:09,120
software almost always because sole proprietors do 
everything. And so you're selling small business  

875
01:19:09,120 --> 01:19:14,080
software like Shopify in the early days and 
there's a lot of other products like that  

876
01:19:14,080 --> 01:19:20,880
where you're trying to sell to small merchants. 
That's great. It doesn't work well when your  

877
01:19:20,880 --> 01:19:25,200
buyer and the user of the software are different. 
So I'll use the example of something like expense  

878
01:19:25,200 --> 01:19:29,120
reporting software. The user of that software 
is an individual employee, but the buyer is  

879
01:19:29,120 --> 01:19:34,720
often a finance department. And so having sign 
up and buy with your credit card doesn't make  

880
01:19:34,720 --> 01:19:39,360
sense because the person using is not the person 
with the credit card and it just doesn't work. 

881
01:19:39,360 --> 01:19:45,360
And then there's direct sales. And direct sales 
had gone, I don't want to say out of fashion,  

882
01:19:45,360 --> 01:19:50,080
but if I think of the best direct sales companies, 
probably there's a lot of lineage from Oracle,  

883
01:19:50,080 --> 01:19:56,400
but you think SAP, Oracle, ServiceNow, Salesforce, 
Adobe perhaps, and there's others as well. And  

884
01:19:56,400 --> 01:20:03,200
these were companies that sold into large lines of 
business in a relatively traditional sales motion.  

885
01:20:03,200 --> 01:20:08,560
I think because product-led growth became very 
popular. I think a lot companies use that, which  

886
01:20:08,560 --> 01:20:18,560
is great, that motion produces great products, 
but if PLG means that you aren't actually engaging  

887
01:20:18,560 --> 01:20:24,400
with the buyer of your software, you're not going 
to grow. And so, I've actually seen more recently,  

888
01:20:24,400 --> 01:20:28,320
with a lot of AI companies, direct sales come 
a little bit more back into fashion because I  

889
01:20:28,320 --> 01:20:35,040
think so many of the opportunities in AI actually 
meet that qualification where the buyer and the  

890
01:20:35,040 --> 01:20:40,480
user are not necessarily the same person and 
it really requires that go-to-market motion. 

891
01:20:40,480 --> 01:20:47,360
Where I see entrepreneurs stumble is they'll 
choose a go-to-market motion without thinking  

892
01:20:47,360 --> 01:20:54,400
through what is the process of purchasing this 
software? What is the process of evaluating the  

893
01:20:54,400 --> 01:20:58,880
value of this software? And I think people 
just need to be much more first principles  

894
01:20:58,880 --> 01:21:03,040
about it and much more thoughtful about it. 
And candidly, I think a lot of companies  

895
01:21:03,040 --> 01:21:08,880
should leverage direct sales more than 
they do. And even though because of the  

896
01:21:09,520 --> 01:21:14,400
sometimes justified reputation of the quality of 
products of some of these direct sales companies,  

897
01:21:14,400 --> 01:21:20,720
it had gotten a bad name. And I think I'm thankful 
to see it coming back in a lot of the AI market.

898
01:21:20,720 --> 01:21:24,000
I feel like this message is something a 
lot of founders need to hear, especially  

899
01:21:24,000 --> 01:21:28,640
founders that aren't from a business 
background that sales turns them off,  

900
01:21:28,640 --> 01:21:32,400
they don't think they're going to be great at 
sales. Just this push of this might be what you  

901
01:21:32,400 --> 01:21:36,480
have to get really good at and this is how you win 
and you can't just rely on product like growth.

902
01:21:36,480 --> 01:21:37,840
Yeah.

